description.narrative: (Ethiopia): .USAID's Building the Potential of Youth (POTENTIAL) provides access to workforce development and livelihood support, which is tailored to youth's specific needs and local market demands. With 70 percent of Ethiopia's population under the age of 30, the youth are disproportionately affected by poverty, conflict, and violence. A core grievance is high youth unemployment, which is a combination of the GOE's inability to create enough jobs and a lack of access to resources. As a stability exporter to the rest of the region, the GOE and the U.S. have recognized the threat that is posed by these youth to Ethiopia's overall stability. By staying attuned to this critical demographic, the U.S. is accelerating Ethiopia's economic journey, while also maintaining broader stability in the Horn of Africa - an American foreign policy objective. ..With FY 2019 funds, POTENTIAL and a future follow-on award, will enable unemployed and underemployed youth aged 15-29, mainly in rural areas, to gain better access to employability knowledge and workforce skills to achieve economic self-sufficiency over the longer term. Specifically, POTENTIAL will target U.S and Ethiopian higher education partnerships to build the capacity of 30 Technical Vocational Education and Training Colleges (TVET). Key activities will include strengthening career guidance and transitions to the labor market and connecting underserved youth, especially women, to employment and income opportunities. FY 2019 funds will also provide the youth with transferable life skills training, linkages with microfinance institutions, and Information and Communication Technologies (ICT) training in rural youth centers to support gainful employment. ... .... .. .
